  "chunk_index": 22,
  "summary": "During a gathering, Poirot discusses the McKitty case, explaining why he does not believe the gloomy tenant, James Bentley, was the killer. The group discusses their whereabouts on the night of November 22nd, the night of Mrs. McGinty's murder. Robin Upward recalls being in Colpeter discussing a janitor character in a play; Hilary Rundle remembers being at her mother's house to keep her company; Mrs. Upward claims she went to bed early due to a headache in a room facing the back garden; and Mollie recalls the baker announcing the murder the following morning.\n\nPoirot presents four photographs as clues. While the others comment on the subjects and fashion, Mrs. Upward claims she recently saw a photograph of a youthful Lily Garfield, though she cannot specify where. After the guests depart, Poirot confronts Mrs. Upward privately. He suggests that her recognition of the photo is dangerous, noting that Mrs. McGinty also recognized a photo before her death. Mrs. Upward remains evasive, stating that her memories are fuzzy and that she needs time to think before acting. She refuses to involve Inspector Spence, claiming it is not the right time. Poirot concludes that Mrs. Upward is a woman who keeps things to herself and has decided to investigate the matter on her own.",
  "summary_whitespace_tokens": 212,
